{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"461df1d3-2bef-4b42-bdbf-0a7b49120bf2","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace** (e.g., 30 seconds):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen load the JSON at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or `kubectl debug` with an ephemeral container.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` or `Ctrl+C` to keep trace size manageable.\n- `--profile cpu-sampling` is lightweight (~5% overhead) and safe for production.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ac6f3490-5be3-4cfe-9020-f2a4b50a691d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":409,"requestId":"980F:36AF0C:CD5CB7:EEC794:69F4025B"},"id":"22ad8587-8051-4a8a-ad22-060d0ea559f3","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:31:18.390Z","parentId":"79f93f43-22e2-4ab3-8b98-d07337212403"}
